description.text: Combination oboe mute and stand. Initially I created this as a mute, but decided to adapt it for use as a stand as well.

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

20% minimum, recommend 50% or higher

Notes:

If used as a stand, use a higher infill percentage to avoid destroying the hole for the screw adapter.

Adding cork to sides of mute

To help hold the mute into the oboe, you'll need to use felt or cork (or Velcro strips). I printed with PLA, so had to lightly sand it and wipe down with acetoone to etch the surface, then placed strips of self-adhesive cork in place. Whatever material/method you use, you'll want to secure the material to the mute, then place the mute into the oboe to allow the oboe's horn to shape the material.

Adapt mute to microphone stand

In order to use the mute as a stand, you'll need to insert a threaded rivet. I chose a 1/4" x 20 rivet, although you can use others. The key is to mate the microphone stand's thread (standard is 5/8" x 17 female thread) to an threaded insert for the mute. The largest threaded insert that I had available for the mute was the 1/4" x 20 insert, so I needed to use threaded adapters to reduce the microphone stand's opening. I didn't see a one-piece 5/8" x 17 to 1/4" x 20, so used a combination of adapters shown, with Loctite to hold them in place.

To insert the threaded rivet to the mute, drill a hole slightly smaller than the rivet, then heat up the rivet with a soldering iron or other heat source, then press into place. To assemble everything, get a 1/4" x 20 screw or bolt at least 1 1/2 inches in length, insert it through the base of the adapted microphone stand, and use a little Loctite to hold it in place.

To use as a mute, unscrew the mute from the base. To use as an oboe stand, screw the mute into the base and gently place the oboe on the stand.

title: Sienci Mill One V2- Level your platform

description.text:
CNC routers can be leveled differently than one would normally level their 3D printer bed. Instead of adjusting the height of 3 or 4 points on the cutting platform to match the router path, an opposite approach can be used. By cutting away at a sacrificial piece of material mounted to the bed of the Mill One, the bed will now be 'level' relative to the routers path.

Download the g-code file and run it so that your machine will automatically perform this operation. Once your sacrificial board is ready, you'll be ready to start cutting on your Mill One!

See more about this process here: https://sienci.com/mill-one-v2-manual/preparing-to-cut/

The rest of the family got easy to buy costumes but I got the Tin Man and just was not happy with a poor selection of Character costumes I could find online. So I decided to make one from scratch. What really set this off was the accessory pieces I was able to model in Fusion 360 and print on my CR-10 printer. Even though the costume was made out of cardboard simply creating and printing the rivets to line the seams and to cover the paper fasteners really brought this character to life. People actually asked me how I bent the metal for this costume. Was proud to present the first true to movie Tin Man heart to Thingiverse as well as the custom nose piece that was secured to my nose using Spirit Gum and covered with face makeup.

I had a hard time finding a funnel that would fit my head so created a close to movie prop replica in fusion as well. This was a really fun project pulled off in just a 7 nights (Mostly Painting). To see the look on my little Dorthy's face when she saw us all in costume was priceless. So proud I could make this happen for her and am thrilled to share with you guys. Enjoy.

remixed_from.title: Rain Gauge for electronic rain sensoring

description.text:
Just made a more complete, ready to print thing out of the original design by Rutgerkdejong. The axle holes are 2mm (from what I remember). You could use some type of nail or wire, etc. for the axle. I just used a little rc car axle I found and cut it to size.

No supports are needed, except for maybe the half circles on the enclosure. I printed that part with support, just for assurance, so I can't say whether it will come out clean without support or not.

The elevated platform on the inside of the enclosure wall is meant to be for whatever sensors you might use to detect the bucket tips. I used a SparkFun line follower (IR detector/emitter) https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9453 . Hot glue this on the side platform, and then glue a square of aluminum foil (for IR reflecting) on the elevated tab on the tipping bucket. I wasn't a fan of the form or function of reed sensors for this application, being how small this setup is, getting the right combination of magnet size/power, distances, etc., didn't seem reliable.

Oh and I allowed enough tolerance between the lid and the enclosure, so you shouldn't have to modify the scaling of either. The files are ready to print.

From my calculations (which may not be totally accurate) with each tip of the bucket, 0.6579mm of rainfall occurs.

If anyone does their own calculations I would be glad to hear them.

description.text:
MOBBOB is really an interesting project and I appreciate the kindness of Kevin Chan, who opened and shared the design source code to the public. These days, I've tried to assemble this cute robot, but I don't want to damage SG90 parts due to some accidents. So, I started to print some spares, include the servo horns (arms).
The horns are used for SG90 servo motor, which is created by FreeCAD. So, if you have some knowledge in using FreeCAD, you can modify the position or diameter of holes by yourself.
Since the flexibility of filament are different, as I've tried two different filament material, and I noticed one of the filament with the same R2.25 cannot be mounted onto SG90 servo. So, I printed another one with R2.3.
If the above two radius are not fit to your own 3D printed horns, you can try to adjust the radius by yourself. The method is finding the object Axis from Fusion->Ring Holder w Gear -> Horn Ring Holder -> Axis. Double click the mouse to open the 2D drawing. Then double click on the radius of 2.3mm or 2.25mm to modify the inner radius. No matter you expand or reduce the radius, it may cause the gear too thin or too thick. So, you need to modify the module of gear, too.
Then, find out the object InvoluteGear from Fusion->Inner Gear->InvoluteGear, double click mouse, and adjust the number of "Modulers" in the 3rd digit behind point. Don't adjust too much. And after the value is changed, the position of gear will be changed (maybe a bug of FreeCad). You need to modify the position of gear by select the InvoluteGear again (single click mouse), and adjust the "Placement, with Z:2mm, Angle:9 degree, and leave the others as it is.
Or if you may like to expand or reduce the width of horns, you can find out the object "sHorn". Double click it to open the 2D drawing screen, simply adjust the distance of the outer virtual circle from the center (same, double click the number of distance, and adjust the value). Then, press "Update" button on the left side. And you will see the width is changed in the 3D drawing. The same method to adjust the position drill hole is the same. Find out the sketch of the hole and adjust the distance.
Finally, select the object "Fusion" and then select the menu File -> Export, then you can get a new STL file.

description.text: Oye! Oye! Brenda the articulated battle tardigrade has been released into the wilds of 3D printing! Join the Horde to be among the first humanoids to learn about the next epic project from Zheng Labs! We now return you to your regular model description.

This last argument of kings uses a single firecracker to launch a festive blast of confetti. Happy birthday, America. Enjoy the schadenfreude of failed prints? Here's the cannon barrel in full-on fail mode: http://t.co/mHMoH7nA

Construction is snap-together! A couple of dabs of glue will keep the carriage from falling apart under the stress of firing. A small piece of bent wire will be very useful in pulling the fuse through the match bore. Firecrackers not included. To load: Crimp a small piece of wire to the tip of a firecracker's fuse. Insert the firecracker into the breech and feed the uncrimped wire end through the match bore. Gently pull the wire out through the match bore and detach it from the fuse. Pack the muzzle with bits of confetti and tamp it down gently with the included rammer. Slide the cap onto the back of the breech, mount the barrel in the carriage, and you're good to go! Light the fuse and get away. For the love of all that's holy, wear eye protection and don't point this at people, animals, or structures. Printing tip: barrel_sprue.stl puts some optional support on the barrel that you can trim off with a knife-- it's for users who wish to print the barrel by itself but are having trouble with a tall, thin print. Fun fact: the ramrod traces its ancestry to a Seej Battle Flag mast.

description.text:
I made this fog machine for my Halloween D&D session, and it turned out perfectly.
It gently mists out fog for 3-4 hours with the size of tank I made (which is as long as we play in a night) and is completely silent, not to mention it could fit inside a soda can.

The module I used is pretty standard and only cost me ten bucks, I'm sure it'll be comparably priced elsewhere

The lid has a cone so the water that hits it will drip back into the tank, and the tank itself has an external fill spot so you don't need to remove the lid to fill it.
Any 40mm fan will fit snugly into the lid, and I've found that the perfect amount of fog flow can be achieved thusly:

-12v 40mm case fan in the lid, powered by a 3.7v Lithium battery
-A square of index card taped over the fan with a 5mm hole in it.
It seems that any larger of a hole allows too much air through and the fog is too thin, but you can play around with it

I've also included a ramp add-on that projects the fog out a little rather than dumping it straight down

Gif of the fog machine in use, and then I plug the fan in

Gif of just the fog pouring over some minis

It also turns out that it'll fit inside a cheap plastic skull!

Warning: If you plan on using this on a gaming table with a TV in it, seal the edges with some painter's tape for the night so the fog doesn't get inside the cabinet and humidify everything

description.text:
This is my take on the belt mounts/tensioner on the CTC I3 Pro B

It is made for GT2 20T Idler with 5mm ID bearing

To assemble you need a countersunk M5 16mm screw, idler and a M5 square nut
To mount it you need a M3 screw, preferably the same that hold the original, M3 nyloc and the original wing nut and washer

It is under construction and I might do some changes

Edit:

I've added another version for the same idler.
It uses a M4 screw and a M4 square nut instead of the M5. To ensure that the idler is in the right place I've added a 0,2mm lip around the hole for the bearing. I've also changed the way to tension it. Now you insert a M3 square nut int to the holder and use a regular screw to tension it from the outside.

Edit 2: I wasn't liking that the X-carriage couldn't use the whole 200mm travel I made another version of the mount. This version is a bit special an requires that the machine is printing almost perfect. This version has a 4,99mm tube that the bearing is "pressed" on to and has a 3,2mm hole through that is for a M3 screw at about 10-12mm. I would recommend that you use a screw that is countersunk and has a head slightly bigger than the bearing ID. Or you could use a hex cap screw that has a OD that matches the bearing ID and use some locking compund, that also requires you to shorten the mounting tube.
The mounting to the ZX-carriage is the same as before with a M3 square nut

Edit 3: I've made yet another version of the X-axis idler pulley. This time a bit slimmer since I've noticed that the previous version was a bit to wide so that the pulley wasn't perfectly aligned.

description.text:
Made of tough yet flexible ABS plastic propeller bumper guards. These weigh, as it turns out, almost a gram. 1.08-1.09 respectively. But as the Proto X only weighs 11.3 grams ANY extra weight will effect flight times and flight characteristics.   
This will tame down the Proto X, puts a little bit of "whoa" on zippy here.   
Very simple and have made flying my Proto X much less prone to prop damage and loss. Not a guarantee, just less likely.   
Must have for beginners and kids until they get the hang of it. And honestly I cruise mine around all the time with it on regardless. Mostly because I am reckless with this little gem on my Proto X. ;0)   
Another bonus I've found is it seems to land on its feet more often with it on. Can't explain it as you would think with the heavier top it would flip on its head, but 8/10 times if I crash I find it right side up.   
Attached with heavy duty double sided tape(provided). I have actually broken the ring more often than before the tape lets loose. Make sure you check your prop clearance for each prop and twist the guard accordingly. I also attach the adhesive to the canopy first and then line up the guard. Make sure to press firmly but don't press hard enough to break your quad.   
Rings are super glue-able. I have a coworker who used hot glue to attach his, but I find that method adds too much weight. Personal opinion.
FDM, 200 micron resolution. 1.75mm ABS. Full Fill. Fine Printing.

Inspired by this and an upcoming delivery of a dozen more threaded taps, I thought I'd better make a holder for my most-used ones.

I didn't want a hole for the wrench like 2200183 as I have at least three different types/sizes of wrench, so I decided to make the middle hole to fit all of the tiny M1-M2.8 taps I have that are only about 3cm long and under 3mm diameter.

I've not made it a Customizer as I don't think the threads library works with that, also there's too many parameters to be practical - like a 2D array of height/diameter for a potentially infinite number of taps! So just download it and pop it into OpenSCAD if you want to edit it.

I also included a Makefile so you can just call make stl to get openscad to render+export it.

Update: switched to English thread as I couldn't get the scale right with metric: 1.0 was too small, 1.03 way too big and it printed stringy. Not printed this version though (slicer says it'll take an hour longer).

title: Webcam mount for Prusa i3 Mk2/S

description.text:
My design for a webcam holder. It should just slide onto the metal frame under the print bed. I designed the camera mount to fit a cheap webcam I had kicking around. I don't know the model of cam, but it is square and has 4 leds on it. I had thought the leds would be brigh enough so I could see the feed with the room lights off but it was not. I ended up getting a Yorkville music stand light. It can be powered by usb so it plugs right into my octopi and give to bright lights an moveable arms.

There are two versions of the arm, I personally like the short version, since I don't print much tall. I use a couple zip ties on it to secure the webcam cable.

The camera mount itself is just a simple square with a connector from tinkercad for articulation. I could see the joint getting loose over time so I might glue it. I used some tape inside to give the camera a bit of friction so it doesn't fall out. If you have a different camera feel free to use my arm design and slap your own mount on it.

title: Spool Tie for PLA Material Spools

description.text:
Here is my version of a Spool Tie for the PLA material. I have found without a tie of some kind the material can get crossed over and bind in use. The tie eliminates this and other issues. I wanted something easy and quick to print. I think it takes about 20 minutes to print three.   
Make sure to snap the Spool Ties onto the spool in the right direction and on the right side of the spool.  See pictures. If you snap on backwards the part will most likely break.  But once snapped onto the spool you leave them there until material is used up.  
The Spool Tie works because it relies on the direction of wind, the outside of the spool and feeding the material thru a hole. The bias is felt thru the hole thus holding the material in place. Reamo

Learn how to design this part: How to Design and 3d Print a Mounted Coat Hanger (Solidworks Tutorial)

I created the coat hanger to replace some really old ones that were mounted. The part was designed in Solidworks. It was printed on my Tevo Tarantula with a 0.5mm nozzle, at 48 mm/s, 0.2mm layer height, no supports, no brim.

Holder for disk radiation samples as available on the internet.  The samples are 25mm in diameter and somewhat less than 3mm thick.  The holder allows the disks to be securely clamped in position.  The hole through the holder allows the radiation to exit without obstruction.

This was my first 3D printing project.  We built it by rotating the holder so that it stood on its edge.  Support approximately 3mm thick was generated to hold the long handle in place.  (I left the support.  It allows the additional option of the sample being held on a surface without the need of a clamp.)
The design should fit on a 10cm by 10cm build surface on a scale of 1 unit equals 1 mm.  It was generated from plastic wire to give it resiliance.  It was a great success.  The sample disk is not perfectly centered around the exit hole but the embedded radioactive material is well within the exit hole so the holder works very well.

title: Leggy Laser Cut Mailbox and Stand

description.text:
This laser cut mailbox features a stand with long legs, a sliding door, and additional shelves for newspapers and packages. The design could be used as an actual mailbox or as some other type of storage unit.

This mailbox was created in Solidworks to make a final laser cut product. Depending on the thickness of your wood, the files may need to be adjusted so that everything fits together properly. This was an issue I ran into when I built the mailbox in 1/8th inch plywood. This design took about 40 minutes to cut, and the model you see in the photos is a half scale model.
